					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/fantem" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1391641); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1391641&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610250576" alt="Fantem" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1391641)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/fantem" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1391641); return false;" >Fantem</a></span> <span class="odate time_1362416751 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">04 Mar 2013 17:05</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1723884">
									

<p>I'm proud to say that that feeling was indeed my intention. ^^</p>
<p>The article states that MalOs tend to try and talk to you, but no one has been able to decipher what they're saying. It also states that 'the more you participate, the more MalO will engage you'.</p>
<p>My interpretation from that, is that they are totally capable of learning how to understand languages from you just talking to them after a while, and either come from somewhere with their own native sign-language, or are just 'programed' to know it.</p>
<p>I'm guessing that if someone with William's symptoms tried to teach a MalO sign-language, they'd be at least partially successful. Although, I'm also guessing their intelligence level is somewhere between a dog's and a monkey's.</p>

							</div>

								
